parameters.content:
## 1. Get Open Tickets
[Read more about the Scheduled Trigger node]({{ $env.WEBHOOK_URL }}

We can use a scheduled trigger to aggressively check for newly open tickets in our JIRA support queue. The "remove duplicates" node (ie. Mark as Seen) is used so that we don't process any issues more than once.

## 2. Automate Triaging of Ticket
[Read more about the Basic LLM node]({{ $env.WEBHOOK_URL }}

New tickets always need to be properly labelled and prioritised but it's not always possible to get to update all incoming tickets if you're light on hands. Using an AI is a great use-case for triaging of tickets as its contextual understanding helps automates this step.

## 3. Attempt to Resolve Ticket Using Previously Resolved Issues
[Learn more about the JIRA node]({{ $env.WEBHOOK_URL }}

There are a number of approaches to also automate issue resolution. Here, we can search for similar tickets in the "Done" or resolved state and using the accepted answers of those tickets, provide context for an AI agent to suggest some ideas back to the user - best case, the fix is found and worst case, the user can add more debugging information through failed attempts.

## 4. Suggest a Resolution via Comment
[Learn more about the JIRA node]({{ $env.WEBHOOK_URL }}

Finally, we provide the context of past resolved tickets for the agent to suggest a few resolution ideas back to the user. Be sure to format the answer to match your company tone of voice as without, AI may sound quite technical and robotic!
